The [3 stone emerald cut diamond ring](/3-stone-emerald-cut-diamond-ring) is the most visually structured engagement ring you can buy. Three rectangles in a row. Step-cut light moving in straight bands across all three stones. When it works, it is the most architectural, most intentional ring on any hand.

When it doesn't work, it's because the buyer focused on the center stone and chose the wrong side stones. The wrong shape. The wrong size ratio. The wrong clarity. These four mistakes cost buyers thousands of dollars and produce rings that look off without being able to say why.

This post is built around those four mistakes — and around the side stone geometry that most jewelers never explain clearly. By the end, you will know exactly which side stone shape to choose, which settings to avoid, and what a complete ring costs with a lab grown center at every budget.

---

**TL;DR**

4 side stone mistakes buyers make on a 3 stone emerald cut diamond ring:
1. Choosing brilliant-cut sides (round, oval, pear) that fight the rectangular geometry
2. Letting side stones exceed 40% of the center stone's width
3. Accepting SI1–SI2 clarity in step-cut side stones (baguettes and trapezoids show inclusions)
4. Paying natural prices for side stones when lab saves 60–70%

→ Best setting: [James Allen Emerald Cut Three Stone Pavé in Platinum at **$3,700**](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/emerald-cut-diamond-three-stone-engagement-ring-with-pave-set-diamonds-in-platinum-by-james-allen-item-304297?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). Pair with a [2ct lab D-FL center at $4,735](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28828463?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) for a complete ring around $8,435.

Priority: get the setting right first. The center stone is replaceable. The geometry of the setting is not.

---

## 4 Side Stone Mistakes 3 Stone Emerald Cut Diamond Ring Buyers Make

### Mistake 1: Choosing Brilliant-Cut Side Stones

Round, oval, and pear side stones are the most popular choices for three-stone rings across all center shapes. They are the wrong choice for an emerald cut center.

Here is why. The emerald cut is a step-cut diamond. Its identity is the rectangular window and the parallel reflections that travel across that table in straight bands. Those reflections create the "hall of mirrors" look. Your eye follows them from corner to corner. The ring reads as a horizontal, architectural piece.

When you put brilliant-cut side stones next to that center, you get competing visual systems. The sides scatter light in every direction. The center moves light in straight lines. The two geometries fight each other. Your eye cannot settle on the ring because the light is doing two completely different things at once.

Step-cut side stones — baguettes, trapezoids, emerald cut sides — echo the center. They move light in the same direction. The ring reads as a unified composition instead of three stones forced into proximity.

Every setting in this post that uses step-cut side stones shows a cleaner, more cohesive ring than any brilliant-cut three-stone design. This is not opinion. It is geometry.

### Mistake 2: Oversized Side Stones

The three-stone ring derives its visual power from contrast. The center stone reads as the main event because it is larger, more prominent, and flanked by its supporters. When the side stones are too large, that hierarchy disappears.

The rule: side stones should not exceed 35–40% of the center stone's face-up width. For a 2ct emerald cut center (approximately 8.0mm × 6.0mm), side stones should be no wider than 2.4mm. This is roughly a 1/8ct or 1/6ct side stone.

When settings list total carat weights like "5/8 ct. tw." or "1/2 ct. tw." for the side stones, that describes both side stones combined. A 5/8 ct. tw. setting means roughly 5/16ct per side — which is on the large end for most center stones under 2ct.

The [Three-Stone Emerald Cut (5/8 ct. tw.) at $4,510](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/three-stone-emerald-cut-diamond-engagement-ring-in-14k-white-gold-5-8-ct-tw-item-203648?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) has included side stones that work well proportionally with a 2–3ct center. For a 1ct center, those sides would be too dominant. Match the side stone size to your center before buying a setting.

### Mistake 3: SI1–SI2 Clarity in Step-Cut Side Stones

Most buyers pay attention to the clarity grade of their center stone. Almost no one thinks about the clarity of the side stones. For the emerald cut three-stone ring, this is a critical oversight.

Baguette and trapezoid side stones are also step cuts. They have the same open-table visibility as the center. SI1 inclusions that hide in a brilliant-cut side stone are visible in a baguette or trapezoid side. You can have a VS1 center flanked by SI1 baguettes and see inclusions in the sides under normal lighting.

The minimum for step-cut side stones is VS2 — and VS1 is safer. When comparing settings, ask about the side stone clarity. Settings that include side stones and list their specs (like the [Bella Vaughan Trapezoid](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/bella-vaughan-trapezoid-three-stone-engagement-ring-in-14k-white-gold-5-8-ct-tw-item-203559?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)) will include this information. For "design your own" settings where you add a separate center stone, the side stones are already part of the setting and their quality is built into the setting price.

### Mistake 4: Paying Natural Prices for Side Stones

Side stones are small. They are set under pressure. They are harder to inspect before purchase than center stones. And yet most buyers automatically choose natural side diamonds alongside their natural or lab center.

Lab grown side diamonds cost 60–70% less than natural at the same grade. In a three-stone ring where the side stones are 1/8ct to 1/4ct each, the total savings are not dramatic in dollar terms — but they are real. More importantly, a setting that includes natural side stones at VS1 clarity is often priced higher than the same setting with lab sides. If you are buying a "design your own" setting and adding a lab grown center, ensure you are not paying a natural-side premium in the setting price.

For complete rings where the setting comes with built-in side stones (like the Gallery Collection or Bella Vaughan designs), the side stones are already included in the setting price and the choice has been made for you.

