## The Side Stone Geometry Rule

This is the framework most jewelers skip. The side stone shape is not a minor aesthetic decision — it is the single factor that determines whether your 3 stone emerald cut diamond ring looks cohesive or confused.

[![Three-stone emerald cut diamond engagement ring with pavé set diamonds in platinum](https://ion.bluenile.com/sets/Jewelry/Photoshoot/Bluenile/BrioSuperImposeBox/Rings/501420/501420_M1_EMR_DIM_wht_0100CT_R_Box3_003_1600X1600.jpg)](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings?styleIDs=three_stone&MetalType=all&Diamonds=Dia&ShapeID=Emerald&a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)

**Baguette side stones** are straight-sided rectangular step cuts. They sit parallel to the center emerald and echo its geometry almost exactly. The ring reads as three rectangular windows in a row, each reflecting light in the same direction. This is the most structured, most vintage-inspired look. It was the dominant choice for Art Deco three-stone rings from the 1920s and 1930s, which is why baguette three-stone rings read as period pieces rather than modern designs. The limitation: baguettes are small and narrow, so they add length to the ring visually without adding much height. The combination is horizontal and elongating.

**Trapezoid side stones** are tapered step cuts — wider on the side facing the center stone and narrowing toward the outside. They frame the center stone differently than baguettes. Instead of sitting as equals, they direct your eye inward toward the center. The tapered shape creates a sense of depth and drawing-in. Trapezoid sides are the choice for buyers who want the three-stone ring to look like a composition, not just three stones in a line. The [Bella Vaughan Trapezoid settings](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/bella-vaughan-trapezoid-three-stone-engagement-ring-in-14k-white-gold-5-8-ct-tw-item-203559?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) represent this style.

**Emerald cut side stones** are the most architecturally pure choice. Center stone and sides are all the same shape — three rectangles. The ring reads as a single unified piece rather than a center plus two flanking elements. The limitation: true emerald cut side stones are harder to find in the right proportion. Most settings labeled "emerald cut three stone" use modified or simplified step cuts for the sides.

**Brilliant-cut side stones** (round, pear, oval, trillion, half-moon) introduce a different optical system alongside the step-cut center — see Mistake 1 above. The exception is the trillion, which sits more quietly alongside an emerald cut center than round or pear because it has a flat table face. But even trilliants scatter light differently than the step center, and the visual conflict is still present.

