## Expert Summary

The 3 stone emerald cut diamond ring is a more demanding design decision than most buyers realize at the start. The center stone is the easy part — choose lab, choose VS1 or better, choose D or E color. Those decisions are clear and the prices are on the page.

The hard part is the side stone geometry. Most jewelry shopping sites let you pick a center stone and a setting separately without telling you whether the side stone shape is right for the emerald cut. The result is that a significant share of three-stone emerald cut rings being built today use the wrong side stones — brilliant cuts that fight the step-cut geometry, or oversized sides that drown the center.

The Side Stone Geometry Rule and the 4 mistakes in this post exist to prevent that outcome. A [JA Pavé Platinum at $3,700](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/emerald-cut-diamond-three-stone-engagement-ring-with-pave-set-diamonds-in-platinum-by-james-allen-item-304297?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) with a [3ct D-IF lab at $9,235](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28885081?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) — total $12,935 — is a better ring than most natural three-stone emerald cuts you could buy for twice the price, not because of the lab stone alone, but because the setting geometry is correct and the clarity is appropriate for the step-cut table.

> "My advice on three-stone emerald cuts is always the same: start with the side stone shape, not the center. Figure out what geometry you want the ring to have. Then pick the center stone that makes that geometry look its best. The buyers who do it the other way around — who pick a beautiful center stone and then try to find a setting for it — often end up with a ring where the stones don't talk to each other."
>
> — Farzana, DiamondCritics

